A Valuation of Aerodrome

Sunny Shi

Sep 17, 2024   18 min read

Key Insights

  • Aerodrome has emerged as the fastest growing EVM DEX this year, largely driven by strong synergies with the Base ecosystem that create a leading destination for trading.
  • The protocol's unique design combines a competitive DEX product with a value-accruing structure that enhances long-term tokenholder returns and participation.
  • Despite concerns about high emissions and untested tokenomics, our model shows that Aerodrome has the potential to sustain and expand its valuation, provided earnings growth exceeds inflation

Aerodrome - The New DEX in Town

It's been a long time since a new decentralized exchange (DEX) has made waves within the EVM ecosystem, with many considering Uniswap's dominance to be a foregone conclusion.

While Uniswap continues to maintain a substantial lead in the sector, Aerodrome has exhibited the fastest growth, quickly positioning itself amongst the top DEXs by trading volume.

On its native chain, Base, Aerodrome has widened its lead in recent months across both trading volumes and total value locked (TVL).

Aerodromes quiet rise to Base dominance has sparked several questions. How does Aerodrome work? What has driven its remarkable growth? And can its current trajectory be sustained? In this report, we explore all of the above and offer a valuation for the AERO token, which sits at the center of the protocols success.

How Does Aerodrome Work?

Aerodrome spun out of its sister DEX on Optimism, Velodrome, with both implementing the same mechanics and being managed by the same team. Before Velodrome, the team operated veDAO, which aimed to function as a voting aggregator for the Fantom DEX Solidly, akin to Convex's role for Curve. Although Solidly launched with a unique design, unfortunate market timing and the quick retirement of its founder Andre Cronje halted growth. Inspired by Solidly's model, Aerodrome and Velodrome sought to rework the protocols vision and expand the concept to different chains.

The MetaDEX - a DEX of the Future

Building off Solidlys initial roadmap, Aerodrome and Velodrome label themselves as MetaDEXs which aim to merge the strongest primitives of previous DEX designs, namely Uniswap and Curve / Convex.

  • From Curve and its token CRV, they draw inspiration from CRV tokenomics to improve DEX governance and value accrual. Curve's early success was partly due to its incentivization primitives, which addressed key weaknesses in Uniswap's design. In Uniswap's model, liquidity providers (LPs) receive 100% of trading fees. While there has been ongoing speculation about activating a protocol "fee switch, such a change would come at the expense of LPs, who have historically been highly mercenary. As a result, the UNI token is stuck in limbo, lacking real value accrual and without a meaningful role in Uniswap Labs agenda. In contrast, Curve distributes its CRV token to LPs and redirects a portion of pool trading fees to CRV lockers. To access that yield, veCRV (vote-escrowed CRV) holders must participate in active governance by voting on the distribution of CRV emissions/incentives across pools. To attract valuable veCRV votes, many protocols resorted to bribing veCRV holders directly to attract liquidity to their own tokens, adding another layer of value to the CRV token. Unlike Uniswap, Curve created a model where DEX value accrual was more evenly distributed among its stakeholders.
  • From Uniswap, they draw inspiration from Uniswap v3 pools. In 2021, Uniswap v3 introduced concentrated liquidity (clAMMs) for liquidity providers (LPs), enabling them to supply liquidity within specific price ranges, typically concentrated where the most trading volume occurs. This innovation significantly enhanced capital efficiency compared to basic Automated Market Makers (AMMs), allowing Uniswap v3 to capture a much higher volume of trades and fees per dollar of deposited TVL. With this breakthrough, Uniswap was able to offer lower fee tiers for v3 pools, which helped it gain market share over competitors like Curve for higher volume pairs. In essence, Uniswap v3 was the best product DEXs could offer at the time, providing the most liquid markets with the best execution for traders.

By tapping into the best aspects of their predecessors, Aerodrome and Velodrome wanted to offer DEXs that could rival the productivity of Uniswap v3 while accruing value to their native tokens similar to Curve.

Well delve into how the team has made this possible with their unique MetaDEX tokenomics.

Aerodromes Tokenomics

As noted earlier, Aerodrome and Velodrome run on the same design. Their tokenomics works as thus:

  • AERO holders who wish to participate and earn yield must lock their AERO tokens to receive vote-escrowed veAERO. Locking for the maximum period of 4 years grants the most voting power, similar to CRV in Curves system.
  • In exchange for voting each epoch, veAERO holders receive 100% of the trading fees generated by the pools they back. This contrasts with Curve, where 50% of all trading fees are distributed proportionally across all veCRV lockers, regardless of their voting behavior.
  • Liquidity providers earn 100% of the protocols AERO emissions for supplying liquidity. This differs from Curve, where LPs earn a mix of trading fees and emissions, with each comprising 50%.
  • Protocols looking to incentivize certain pools can deposit their incentive assets, which are distributed to the voters who support those pools.

Abstracting away the different assets involved, Aerodrome operates on a straightforward business model. veAERO holders are essentially the business owners of the exchange, taking on risk by purchasing and locking AERO tokens, and making key decisions. They pay LPs to provide liquidity, while traders and protocols pay veAERO holders to manage that liquidity.

Rather than LPs acting as mercenaries, here they function as service providers. veAERO voters control liquidity levels by directing AERO emissions to specific pools for LPs to earn.

This design offers several key advantages over Curves model.

  • Unlike Curve, where voters may prioritize bribes because they earn the same trading fee rewards regardless of which pools they vote for, veAERO holders are incentivized to support productive markets. Their returns depend on both bribes and the trading fees generated by the pools they back.
  • Since 100% of AERO emissions go to LPs, veAERO voters exert greater influence over liquidity on the DEX. With Curve, veCRV holders could only allocate 50% of emissions to liquidity providers which dwindled as emissions decreased, reducing flexibility. As an example, during a bear market when trading fees are depressed, veAERO voters can concentrate 100% of their emissions to critical pools to boost the DEXs market share in the short term until volume returns. veAERO holders will also have the added functionality of adjusting emissions as needed, whereas Curve emissions were fixed.

Voters have diverse motivations based on their priorities and activity levels:

  • Coinbase Ventures, which owns veAERO, may opt to support their portfolio companies and accumulate their underlying tokens.
  • Voters aiming to maximize trading fees might direct voting power to Aerodromes concentrated liquidity pools, focusing on high-volume pools that pay fees in stable assets like ETH and USDC.
  • Speculators bullish on certain memecoins may vote for those pairs to front-run volume and accumulate more tokens.
  • Short term return-oriented voters could simply allocate to the highest APR pools each epoch, targeting those offering the most bribes alongside trading fees.

In general, voter returns are fully aligned with the DEXs productivity, which allows for active contribution to the growth of the DEX.

However, to outcompete Uniswap and succeed where Curve could not, Aerodrome and Velodrome must reach product parity by developing an AMM that matches the capital efficiency of Uniswap v3.

Slipstream vs. Uniswap v3

Slipstream is the teams implementation of a clAMM, and introduced not only concentrated liquidity but also additional features designed to enhance the LP experience. This includes wider tick spaces for less sophisticated LPs and Slipstreams Gauge Rewards which smooths out returns over time, ensuring more consistent liquidity during days of lower trading volume.

With a competitive clAMM in place, Aerodrome and Velodromes tokenomic enhancements shine.

So far, the implementation has been successful, with both Velodrome and Aerodrome generating higher trading volumes than Uniswap on their respective chains, while returning 100% of trading fees directly to their tokenholders.

With value-accruing tokens in play, Aerodrome and Velodrome hold a distinct advantage over Uniswap due to their ability to bootstrap liquidity more rapidly by leveraging them as strategic tools. As of this writing, when reviewing trending pools with liquidity exceeding $1 million on Base, Aerodrome features 17 on Slipstream and 20 on Basic, compared to 9 on Uniswap v3 and just 1 on Uniswap v2. Through AERO emissions, LPs are reaping substantial APRs:

Instead of creating a zero-sum conflict between tokenholders and LPs over fees (as would be the case for Uniswap), Aerodrome and Velodrome have, for the time being, successfully maintained a balance that keeps both parties satisfied. From here, the protocols ability to maintain that dynamic becomes the focus.

What has Driven Aerodromes Growth?

This report centers on Aerodrome rather than Velodrome for the simple reason that Aerodrome has experienced more significant growth, despite being the newer protocol. We believe Aerodrome has largely achieved this due to its synergistic relationship with the Base L2.

Base and Aerodrome - a Match Made in Heaven

A compelling case study is emerging that highlights the combined value proposition of Base and Aerodrome. On a weekly basis, ~$70 billion of volume trades spot Ethereum (ETH) across both CEXs and DEXs. However, the focal point for onchain spot ETH trading has shifted to Aerodrome on Base.

Aerodrome Slipstreams WETH/USDC pool frequently ranks as the top onchain ETH trading venue and, on certain days, even surpasses major CEXs in volume. When analyzing Aerodromes volume drivers, the WETH/USDC pool is indeed an outsized contributor, accounting for ~75% of total DEX volumes since its introduction.

Why is there so much ETH trading activity congregating on Base? To unpack this development, its first crucial to understand what Base has done to create value.

  • Base has been hyper focused on lowering gas fees on the platform. So far, these efforts have yielded great results. Despite being the most transacted on ETH L2, Base offers some of the most competitive gas prices for users.
  • Additionally, Coinbase has streamlined the process for users to move assets from its centralized exchange to Base. In July, Coinbase announced that they would be waiving transfer fees from onramping to Base, marking one of the only onramp methods in crypto that is completely free.

We believe that Aerodromes ETH trading dominance is almost entirely driven by the factors mentioned above in conjunction with Aerodromes capital efficiency and liquidity depth.

  • High-frequency-traders benefit from Bases low gas fees.
  • Traders seeking optimal execution for ETH can find it in Aerodrome Slipstreams low-slippage, high-TVL WETH/USDC pool.
  • Arbitrageurs exploiting price differences between CEXs and DEXs enjoy a zero-fee onramp through Coinbase to Base.

In conclusion, the synergy between Aerodrome and Bases superior user experience (UX) has been the most significant contribution for Aerodromes early growth.

Is Aerodromes Growth Sustainable?

Given Aerodromes high rate of emissions, the biggest trial for the protocol from here is to prove that it has staying power. We believe the sustainability of the DEX is tied to a simple metric:

  • In the long term, earnings growth for veAERO lockers has to outpace the rate of inflation for the AERO token.

This is a function of three main drivers:

  • Base needs to remain in a state of growth.
  • Token emissions need to find equilibrium.
  • The AERO token has to find support

Future Growth Drivers

Lets look at some potential growth drivers.

Base Growth

Arguably the most crucial growth driver for Aerodrome is the necessity for Base to maintain its status as a hot onchain destination. Increased activity on the L2 directly translates into higher trading volumes, which will, in turn, boost fees distributed to veAERO holders. Similarly, as more protocols onboard to Base, the demand for Aerodromes emissions will rise, leading to increased bribing activity.

With Coinbase making Base a top priority within their business strategy, ongoing efforts will be made to expand and strengthen the ecosystem.

cbBTC as a Catalyst

Looking ahead, there is a clear opportunity to replicate the success of the Slipstream WETH/USDC pool with other trading pairs on Aerodrome. The most promising candidate is cbBTC, Coinbase's newly announced ERC-20 wrapped Bitcoin asset, backed by Coinbase's substantial Bitcoin reserves.

Growing concerns around the sustainability of wBTC on Ethereum further strengthen the cbBTC narrative. Since its launch on September 12th, cbBTC has generated significant early interest, driving strong growth in TVL for cbBTC pairs on Aerodrome.

Managing Emissions

As of this writing, Aerodrome is in epoch 55 of its lifecycle, with each epoch lasting one week. After the conclusion of epoch 67, emissions will transition from a fixed schedule to a variable input controlled by token lockers.

This change grants AERO holders significantly greater flexibility in controlling their supply growth. Aerodrome aims to function as a sort of Federal Reserve for Base, injecting liquidity into the ecosystem when necessary and curbing inflation when the market overheats.

The Aerodrome Lifecycle

It is important to note that Aerodrome will experience different stages in its protocol lifecycle. Currently, emissions exceed fee and bribe rewards for AERO, which is intentional, as growth is the primary focus. As the protocol matures, growth in fee and bribe rewards will need to surpass the token inflation rate, driven by both revenue expansion and tightened emissions. Over time as volatility ensues, AERO will likely have to sacrifice profitability during periods of slower demand and regain it when demand accelerates, all while working towards a profitable longer-term trajectory.

Support for the AERO Token

The major vulnerability of protocols that rely on tokens to incentivize specific behaviorsand Aerodrome's greatest riskis the potential for the AERO token to lose significant value, thereby weakening its capacity to drive stimulus within the protocol. If AERO experiences an extended period of depressed price action, DEX liquidity will inevitably decline, as LPs will face contracting APRs. This is often referred to as a death spiral.

However, it's important to distinguish between protocols with tokens that carry no utility and those backed by tokens with real utility. Given Aerodrome's pivotal role within the Base ecosystem, we believe this risk can be mitigated by two potential backstops that could provide support to AEROs valuation:

  • First, if the value of liquidity on Base remains high, there will always be demand for veAERO, as buyers can accumulate the token to influence emissions toward specific trading pairs. For instance, Coinbase Ventures may find the opportunity to increase their voting power too valuable to overlook. Additionally, protocols themselves may start purchasing veAERO to better incentivize liquidity in their own pools.
  • Second, since veAERO yield can be paid in various assets (ETH, USDC, protocol tokens, etc.), there comes a point where the dividend yield from veAERO becomes too high to ignore. According to our model, if veAERO locking rates were to halve, the combined average APRs from bribes and fees would exceed 100%.

This does not indicate in any way that Aerodromes model is infallible. Rather, Aerodrome has reached a level of growth sufficient to provide tangible value to the AERO token, greatly boosting its survivability.

Valuation

Lets incorporate the factors above into a model, where we attempt to pin down a valuation method for the AERO token.

Assumptions

Firstly, well review the core assumptions.

Growth Assumptions

  • Growth assumptions are based on Base's ability to increase its share of overall crypto DEX volumes. In our base case, we project Base reaching 15% of total DEX volumes by the end of 2026, compared to 8% in Q2 2024. We believe in Bases share capture story, due to Coinbases winning product-oriented mindset and ongoing efforts to introduce new assets to Base, such as cbBTC.
  • Aerodrome's market share within Base's DEX volumes is also modeled. Currently, Aerodrome Slipstream holds ~85% market share against Uniswap v3. We project Aerodrome's total volume share to rise to 90% by the end of 2026 as they continue to out-execute Uniswap on their native chain.
  • Aerodromes trading fee take rate for both Slipstream and Basic is assumed to remain constant throughout the projection period.
  • We project 5% quarter-over-quarter growth in bribes for Aerodrome Basic as Base's onchain ecosystem expands and more protocols begin offering bribes.
  • Slipstream bribes are expected to remain flat at 0% growth, as protocols tend to focus their incentives on more accessible Basic AMM pools.

Supply Assumptions

  • We project future $AERO emissions based on set LP emission rates up to epoch 67.
  • After epoch 67, we assume the quantity of AERO emitted each quarter remains constant.

Valuation Method

To account for the impact of inflation, we use a diluted EPS method to represent earnings power, capturing the emission cost to veAERO holders. Lockers prioritize maximizing bribe and fee yields which is moreso impacted by the amount of circulating AERO that could be locked vs. the dollar amount of LP emissions. This makes diluted EPS a better reflection of holder sentiment vs. modeling emissions as a direct cost.

Our bear, base, and bull case results support the sustainability arguments made above.

Bear Case:

  • In the bear case, veAERO earnings growth does not outpace AERO inflation, resulting in declining diluted EPS despite nominal growth in total earnings.
  • We believe the market will not assign a high multiple to a protocol experiencing shrinking EPS, so we use a 5x multiple for this scenario.

Base Case:

  • In the base case, earnings growth exceeds inflation, resulting in growth in diluted EPS.
  • Given modest EPS growth in this scenario, we apply a 7.5x multiple.

Bull Case

  • In the bull case, strong earnings growth significantly outpaces inflation, leading to a near 2x of diluted EPS from 2024 to 2026.
  • Given the robust growth, we apply a 10x multiple in this scenario.

Our final valuation ranges offer a clear perspective on how to assess the AERO asset. Despite positive earnings growth across our scenarios, AERO's valuation declines with each passing year if emissions are diluting per-share returns for veAERO holders. However, there remains significant potential for AEROs valuation to expand, provided that earnings growth continues to outpace inflation and remains accretive.

It is also important to note that veAERO lockers are earning real yield throughout the duration of their hold period. We note that in our base case, at a 50% locked ratio (where current ratios have stabilized around), veAERO holders achieve an average APR of 47-66% for actively voting. This represents a weekly dividend, paid out in a number of possible underlying assets that adds to any principal appreciation.

Implications

Given the prevalent skepticism surrounding high-inflation tokens in crypto, its crucial to examine how inflation is integrated into each protocol's economic output and whether the protocol is effectively accruing value for tokenholders while expanding earnings growth.

When we assess Aerodromes implied outcomes through a model, it's evident that token inflation, in itself, is not inherently bad. Instead, emissions are just one input into an economic modela cost that can be managed and overcome. To draw a comparison, tech companies listed on the Nasdaq have often relied on stock-based compensation and share inflation to bootstrap productivity in their earlier stages, before reaching an end state of sustained diluted EPS growth.

Risks

Some notable risks include:

  • Ecosystem risk poses a threat. If Base struggles due to poor execution, intensifying L1/L2 competition, or waning user interest, Aerodrome will likely underperform.
  • Aerodrome-specific risks, as discussed earlier, include the potential for a token "death spiral," which could undermine liquidity incentives, as well as challenges in balancing growth with controlled emissions.
  • Uniswap v4, or future iterations, may prove to be the winning DEX model yet again.
  • DEXs are vulnerable to vampire attacks, and Aerodrome may face challenges from emerging competitors offering their own aggressive incentives.
  • Negative connotations around highly inflationary protocols may prevent upside.

Conclusion

With so few projects in crypto capable of delivering real value accrual, Aerodrome represents a bold new effort to reinvent DEXs for the better. The results so far have been promising, with the protocol achieving substantial volume growth all while returning a significant portion of the value generated back to its tokenholders. While untested tokenomics and high emissions raise concerns about long-term sustainability, a closer examination shows that Aerodrome has the potential to maintain a growing valuation, even within an inflationary framework.
